## Error Handling

### Error Classes

```python
# app/infrastructure/errors/app_error.py
class AppError(Exception):
    def __init__(self, message: str, status_code: int = 500) -> None:
        super().__init__(message)
        self.status_code = status_code


# app/infrastructure/errors/validation_error.py
class DomainValidationError(Exception):
    pass
```

### Global Exception Handler

```python
# main.py
from fastapi import FastAPI, Request
from fastapi.responses import JSONResponse
from app.infrastructure.errors.app_error import AppError
from app.infrastructure.errors.validation_error import DomainValidationError

app = FastAPI()

@app.exception_handler(AppError)
async def app_error_handler(request: Request, exc: AppError) -> JSONResponse:
    return JSONResponse(status_code=exc.status_code, content={"error": str(exc)})

@app.exception_handler(DomainValidationError)
async def validation_error_handler(request: Request, exc: DomainValidationError) -> JSONResponse:
    return JSONResponse(status_code=400, content={"error": str(exc)})
```

### HTTP Status Code Mapping

| Error | Status |
|---|---|
| `DomainValidationError` | 400 |
| `HTTPException` (not found) | 404 |
| `AppError` (custom) | per `status_code` |
| Unhandled | 500 |

### Response Format

All error responses follow this shape:
```json
{ "error": "Human-readable message" }
```

